form\"/> As a result of the success of Baldur's Gate, Ohlen was made the company's Director of Design. He continued to work as the lead designer on BioWare's Dungeons and Dragons titles including Baldur's Gate 2 and Neverwinter Nights. He later led up the design on ''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic]]'' and Dragon Age: Origins.<ref>(November 4, 2008). \"New 'Star Wars' online game is 4-millennium rewind\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', p. 32.</ref>\n\nIn 2006 James Ohlen moved to Austin, Texas to set up a new studio for BioWare alongside Gordon Walton and Rich Vogel. That studio was responsible for the production of the MMORPG game ''[[Star Wars: The Old Republic]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bioware Opens Austin MMORPG Studio |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2006/03/13/bioware-opens-austin-mmorpg-studio |publisher=IGN |date=13 March 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Ohlen retired from BioWare after 22 years to start up his own publishing company \u2013 Arcanum Worlds.<ref name=\"ENG\">{{cite news |last1=Moon |first1=Mariella |title='Baldur's Gate' designer James Ohlen leaves BioWare after 22 years |url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/07/13/baldurs-gate-james-ohlen-bioware-departure/ |publisher=Engadget |date=13 July 2018}}</ref> The first book to be produced by Arcanum Worlds is ''Odyssey of the Dragonlords''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lanier |first1=Liz |title=James Ohlen Retires From BioWare, Working on Dungeons and Dragons Book |url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/james-ohlen-retires-bioware-new-dungeons-and-dragons-book-1202872662/ |publisher=Variety |date=13 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Wizards of the Coast]] announced it was establishing a new Austin-based studio in April 2019 to develop new intellectual properties (IP), and had tapped Ohlen to lead it. Ohlen said that the offer was too good to pass up, and that \"This is just an opportunity to work on projects as personal to me as the good ol' days of the '90s and early '00s.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-04-24-james-ohlen-joins-wizards-of-the-coast |title = James Ohlen joins Wizards of the Coast | first= Brendan | last= Sinclair | date = April 24, 2019 | accessdate = February 13, 2020 | work = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] }}</ref> By January 2020, Wizards of the Coast revealed the studio as [[Archetype Entertainment]], and that another former BioWare member, Chad Robertson, was named as vice-president and general manager.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-01-31-ex-bioware-vets-working-on-story-driven-sci-fi-game-at-new-wizards-of-the-coast-studio | title = Ex-BioWare vets working on story-driven sci-fi game at new Wizards of the Coast studio | first=  Matt | last = Wales | date = January 31, 2020 | accessdate = February 13, 2020 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> A month later, [[Drew Karpyshyn]], yet another former BioWare member, came onboard Archetype as lead writer.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-02-12-mass-effect-lead-writer-drew-karpyshyn-joins-ex-bioware-vets-new-wizards-of-the-coast-studio | title = Mass Effect lead writer Drew Karpyshyn joins ex-BioWare vets' new Wizards of the Coast studio | first =Matt | last = Wales | date = February 12, 2020 | accessdate = February 12, 2020  |work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> Ohlen was able to continue Arcanum Worlds under the deal, though the studio would not use any of the IP developed through Arcanum.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://venturebeat.com/2019/04/24/wizards-of-the-coast-taps-baldurs-gate-star-wars-knights-of-the-old-republic-designer-james-ohlen-for-new-studio/ | title = Wizards of the Coast taps Baldur\u2019s Gate, Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic designer James Ohlen for new studio | first = Jason | last =Wilson  |date = April 24, 2019 | accessdate = February 13, 2020  |work = [[Venture Beat]] }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\n===As Lead Designer/Creative Director===\n* ''[[Baldur's Gate]]'' (1998)<ref name=\"Euro\">{{cite news |last1=Purchese |first1=Robert |title=Decorated designer James Ohlen retires from BioWare after 22 years |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-07-13-decorated-designer-james-ohlen-retires-from-bioware-after-22-years |publisher=Eurogamer |date=13 July 2018}}</ref>\n* ''[[Baldur's Gate: Tales of the Sword Coast]]'' (1999)<ref name=\"Euro\"/>\n* ''[[Baldur's Gate II: Shadows of Amn]]'' (2000)<ref name=\"Euro\"/>\n* ''[[Neverwinter Nights]]'' (2002)<ref name=\"Euro\"/>\n* ''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic]]'' (2003)<ref name=\"Euro\"/>\n* ''[[Dragon Age: Origins]]'' (2008)<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dammes |first1=Matthias |title=Report: Ist Bioware wirklich noch Bioware? |url=http://www.pcgames.de/Bioware-Firma-15280/Specials/Report-Ist-Bioware-wirklich-noch-Bioware-1225127/ |publisher=PC Games |date=4 November 2017 |language=German}}</ref>\n* ''[[Star Wars: The Old Republic]]'' (2011)<ref>{{cite news |title=New 'Star Wars The Old Republic' Expansion: Free Trial Of Prequel Story Live |url=https://www.inquisitr.com/3316865/new-star-wars-the-old-republic-expansion-free-trial-of-prequel-story-live/ |publisher=Inquisitr |date=17 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Other Games===\n* ''[[Shattered Steel]]'' (1997)<ref name=\"GInform\"/>\n* ''[[Jade Empire]]'' (2005)<ref name=\"GBS\">{{cite news |title=BioWare's James Ohlen Talks Game Design |url=http://www.gamebanshee.com/news/118971-bioware-s-james-ohlen-talks-game-design.html |publisher=Game Banshee |date=23 May 2017}}</ref>\n* ''[[Mass Effect (video game)|Mass Effect]]'' (2007)<ref name=\"GBS\"/>\n* ''[[Anthem (video game)|Anthem]]'' (2019)<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donnelly |first1=Joe |title=If Anthem doesn't succeed, it won't be the end of BioWare, thinks ex-studio designer |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/if-anthem-doesnt-succeed-it-wont-be-the-end-of-bioware-thinks-ex-studio-designer/ |publisher=PC Gamer |date=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.arcanumworlds.com/ Arcanum Worlds official website]\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.bioware.com/10years/10_years_of_bioware.html |title=10 Years of Bioware Interview|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061025011700/http://www.bioware.com/10years/10_years_of_bioware.html|archivedate=October 25, 2006}}\n* {{moby developer|id=6525}}\n\n{{Bioware}}\n{{D&D topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ohlen, James}}\n[[Category:BioWare people]]\n[[Category:Canadian video game designers]]\n[[Category:Dungeons & Dragons video game designers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{videogame-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nealbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:clean up, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Ohlen"}
{"title_page": "Boeing Business Jet", "text_new": "{{short description|Executive transport variants of several Boeing airliners}}\n<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox aircraft begin\n| name = Boeing Business Jet\n| image = Boeing's commercial aircraft in BBJ livery.jpg\n| caption = Artist's impression of the entire BBJ family\n}}{{Infobox aircraft type\n| type = [[Business jet]]\n| manufacturer = [[Boeing Commercial Airplanes]]\n| designer = \n| first flight = September 4, 1998\n| introduced = 1999\n| retired = \n| status = \n| primary user = \n| more users = \n| produced = 1998\u2013present\n| number built = 237 (as of December 31, 2018) (including BBJ1, BBJ2, BBJ3, 747BBJ, 757BBJ, 767BBJ, 777BBJ & 787BBJ)<ref name=\"boeing.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boeing.com/commercial/bbj/#/orders-and-deliveries|title=Boeing: Boeing Business Jets|author=|date=|website=boeing.com|accessdate=23 February 2019}}</ref>\n| unit cost = MAX7: [[United States dollar|US$]]91.2M, MAX8: $99M, MAX9: $107.9M (2019)<ref name=BCA-2019>{{cite magazine |url= https://aviationweek.com/site-files/aviationweek.com/files/datasheets/gated/BCA_201906.pdf |title= Purchase Planning Handbook |magazine= Business & Commercial Aviation |date= June 2019 |publisher= Aviation Week Network |url-access= subscription}}</ref>\n| developed from = \n| variants with their own articles = \n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Boeing Business Jet''' series are variants of [[Boeing Commercial Airplanes|Boeing]] [[jet airliner]]s for the [[corporate jet]] market.\n\nThe '''BBJ''' designation denotes the business jets based upon the [[Boeing 737|737]] series airliners. These aircraft usually seat between 25 and 50 passengers within a luxurious configuration. This may include a master bedroom, a washroom with showers, a conference/dining area, and a living area. Boeing Business Jets also has corporate jet configurations based on the [[Boeing 737 MAX|737 MAX]], [[Boeing 777x|777X]], [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner|787 Dreamliner]] and [[Boeing 747-8|747-8 Intercontinental]], which are known as '''737 MAX VIP''', '''777X VIP''', '''787 VIP''', and '''747-8 VIP''', respectively.\n\nThe BBJ division offers 11 products derived from Boeing's airliners.<ref name=ain2015-05-16>{{cite news |first=Kerry |last=Lynch |url=http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/business-aviation/2015-05-16/boeing-business-jets-confident-it-studies-combi |title=Boeing Business Jets confident as it studies Combi |work=Aviation International News |date= 16 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Models==\n\n===Narrow-body models===\n[[File:Boeing 737-75V BBJ AN1425895.jpg|thumb|BBJ cabin]]\n\n<!--design-->\nThe first BBJ is based on the [[737-700]] with a stronger wing and landing gear from the [[737-800]].<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nAuxiliary belly fuel tanks extend range, over {{cvt|6,000|nmi|km}} with nine tanks ({{cvt|500|lb|kg}} empty each), but most operators install five auxiliary fuel tanks to fly up to {{cvt|5,400|nmi|km}}.<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nIn 2002, the -800-based BBJ2 offered a 25% larger cabin with a similar range with five tanks, with the 2009 BBJ3 based on the [[737-900]].<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\n[[Aviation Partners]] winglets gave the BBJ 5% more range.<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nA standard, retractable forward [[airstair]] allows for autonomous operations at remote airports.<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nEarly interiors were way over the {{cvt|13,000|lb|t}} allowance and the [[basic operating weight|BOW]]s reached {{cvt|104,000\u20138,000|lb}} over spec, but newer interiors can be 25% lighter for {{cvt|99,000\u2013100,000|lb|t}} empty weights.<ref name=BCA7jan2019/>\n\n<!--performance-->\nFuel burn is {{cvt|4,830|lb|t}} per hour at Mach 0.785, rising to over {{cvt|5,700|lb|t}} at Mach 0.82, twice as much as a faster [[Global 6000]].<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\n<!--maintenance-->\nDirect operating costs are $14,000 per hour, minor inspections come every 36 months and major inspections at 12-year for a 4\u20138 weeks down time.<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nAt 41,000 ft, cabin altitude can be lowered from 8,000&nbsp;ft to 6,500&nbsp;ft, but it reduces airframe life to 26,000 down from 50,000 cycles, much higher than purpose-built business jets.<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nMost operators fly their aircraft 200\u2013250 h per year with 6\u20138 passengers, 500\u2013800 h for corporations to less than 150\u2013200 h for individuals.<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nThe CFM56 service program costs $240\u2013260 per engine per hour, less than the [[Rolls-Royce BR700]], with the engines staying on wing for at least 12,000\u201313,000 h for most, and up to 25,000\u201330,000 h.<ref name=BCA7jan2019/>\n[[Fokker Technologies#Business units|Fokker Services]] were developing {{cvt|1.5|meter}} wide windows for the BBJ in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/business-aviation/2015-05-20/first-skyview-bbj|title=First SkyView for BBJ|author= David Donald |date= May 20, 2015 |work=AIN online}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/ebace-fokker-proposes-giant-window-to-boeing-business-399588/ |title= Fokker proposes giant window to Boeing Business Jets |date= 13 Apr 2015 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n<!-- operators-->\nTwenty years after the 1999 introduction, 150 BBJs had entered service, triple the initial forecast of 50. The 2008 recession put ultra large jets under scrutiny and were divested by some companies. Some BBJs are operated by governments for [[VIP transport]].<ref name=BCA7jan2019>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/business-aviation/boeing-business-jet-why-go-big-because-you-can |title= Boeing Business Jet: Why Go Big? Because You Can |date= Jan 7, 2019 |author= Fred George |work= Business & Commercial Aviation}}</ref>\n\n<!--competition-->\nAfter the launch of the BBJ, [[Airbus]] followed suit with the launch of the [[Airbus Corporate Jets|Airbus ACJ]] derived from its [[Airbus A319|A319]] airliner, then the larger A320 and the smaller [[Airbus A318|A318]] Elite. Other smaller competitors include the [[Embraer Lineage]], the [[Bombardier Global Express]], the [[Gulfstream G550]] and the [[Gulfstream G650]]. A BBJ costs {{usd|9.57\u201310.13}} per nautical mile to operate, whereas the faster G650ER costs $5.87 to 6.33.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviationweek.com/site-files/aviationweek.com/files/gallery_images/BCA_2015_Operations_Planning_Guide_6b.jpg?1440787936|title= Mission Costs for Ultra-Long-Range Jets Table|work= Aviation Week |date= May 2015}}</ref>\n\n* '''BBJ''', or less frequently '''BBJ1''', is based on the 737-700, and formed the basis for the 737-700ER. This was the initial variant. In [[United States Navy]] service, this is known as the [[Boeing C-40 Clipper|C-40B Clipper]].\n* '''BBJ2''' is based on the 737-800.\n* '''BBJ3''' is based on the 737-900ER.\n* '''BBJ C''' is a variant of the BBJ featuring the \"quick change\" capabilities of the 737-700C. This allows the aircraft to be used for executive duty during one flight, and to be quickly reconfigured for cargo duty for the next flight.\n* '''BBJ MAX 8''' and '''BBJ MAX 9''' are variants of the [[Boeing 737 MAX]] 8 and 9 with new [[CFM LEAP]]-1B engines and advanced winglets providing 13% better fuel burn; the BBJ MAX 8 will have a {{cvt|6,325|nmi|km|-1}} range and the BBJ MAX 9 a {{cvt|6,255|nmi|km|-1}} range.<ref>{{cite press release |url= http://boeing.mediaroom.com/2012-10-29-Boeing-Business-Jets-to-Offer-the-BBJ-MAX |title= Boeing Business Jets to Offer the BBJ MAX |publisher= Boeing |date= October 29, 2012 |access-date=October 30, 2012}}</ref> The '''BBJ MAX 7''' was unveiled in October 2016 and will have a {{cvt|7,000|nmi|km|-1}} range, with 10% lower operating costs than the original BBJ while having a longer cabin and more under-floor baggage space.<ref>{{cite press release |url= http://boeing.mediaroom.com/news-releases-statements?item=129797 |title= Boeing Business Jets Unveils BBJ MAX 7 |date= October 31, 2016 |publisher= Boeing |access-date=November 1, 2016}}</ref> The MAX BBJ 8 first flew on April 16, 2018, and will reach {{cvt|6,640|nmi|km|-1}} with an auxiliary fuel tank.<ref>{{cite press release |url= http://boeing.mediaroom.com/2018-04-16-Boeing-Business-Jets-Celebrates-Flyaway-of-First-BBJ-MAX-Airplane |title= Milestone paves the way for delivery of the newest version of the best-selling business jetliner |date= April 16, 2018 |publisher= Boeing}}</ref> It was first delivered by mid-October.<ref>{{cite press release |url= https://boeing.mediaroom.com/2018-10-15-Boeing-Business-Jets-Delivers-First-BBJ-MAX-Airplane |title= Boeing Business Jets Delivers First BBJ MAX Airplane |date= Oct 15, 2018 |publisher= Boeing}}</ref>\n\n{{seealso|Boeing 737 MAX groundings}}\n\n====Specifications====\n{| style=\"text-align: center\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Boeing Business Jets<ref name=BBJ>{{cite web |url= https://www.boeing.com/commercial/bbj |title= Boeing Business Jets |date= December 2018 |publisher= Boeing}}</ref>\n|-\n! Variant !! BBJ MAX 7 !! BBJ MAX 8 !! BBJ MAX 9 \n|- \n! Cabin\n| 884 sq ft / 82.1 m\u00b2\n| 1,025 sq ft / 95.2 m\u00b2\n| 1,120 sq ft / 104.1 m\u00b2 \n|- \n! Cargo \n| 274 cu.ft / 7.8 m\u00b3\n| 654 cu.ft / 18.5 m\u00b3\n| 821 cu.ft /23.2 m\u00b3\n|- \n! Length\n| 116&nbsp;ft 8 in / 35.56 m\n| 129&nbsp;ft 8 in / 39.52 m\n| 138&nbsp;ft 4 in / 42.16 m\n|- \n! Span \u00d7 Height\n| colspan=3 | 117&nbsp;ft 10 in / 35.92 m \u00d7 40&nbsp;ft 4 in / 12.3 m\n|-  \n! [[Maximum takeoff weight|MTOW]]\n| 177,000&nbsp;lb / 80,286&nbsp;kg\n| 181,200&nbsp;lb / 82,191&nbsp;kg\n| 194,700&nbsp;lb / 88,314&nbsp;kg\n|-  \n! max [[Payload]] <!-- = Maximum zero fuel weight - OEW-->\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:138700-106330}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:145400-109890}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:156500-117900}}|lb|kg|0}}\n|-  \n! [[Operating empty weight|OEW]]\n| {{cvt|106,330|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|109,890|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|117,900|lb|kg|0}}\n|-\n! Furnishings\n| {{cvt|16,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|18,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|21,000|lb|kg|0}}\n|-\n! [[Manufacturer's empty weight|MEW]] <!-- = OEW - interior allowance-->\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:106330-16000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:109890-18000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:117900-21000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n|-\n! Fuel capacity{{efn|auxiliary tanks: 7 for MAX 7/8, 8 for MAX 9}}\n| {{cvt|10,464|USgal|l|0}}\n| {{cvt|10,470|USgal|l|0}}\n| {{cvt|11,005|USgal|l|0}}\n|-\n! Engines (2\u00d7)\n| colspan=3 | [[CFM International LEAP]]\n|-\n! Range (8 pax)\n| {{cvt|7,000|nmi|km|0}}\n| {{cvt|6,640|nmi|km|0}}\n| {{cvt|6,515|nmi|km|0}}\n|}\n\n===Wide-body models===\n\n{{multiple image\n | direction = vertical\n | image1 = A7-HBJ 03122015LHR (23226682739) (cropped).jpg\n | width1 = 250\n | caption1 = [[Qatar Amiri Flight]] 747-8 VIP\n | image2 = Boeing 777-24Q-ER AN0433002 (cropped).jpg\n | width2 = 250\n | caption2  = [[Mid East Jet]] 777-200 VIP\n | image4 = Jet Aviation Flight Services, Boeing 787-8 Dreamliner, N28MS (cropped).jpg\n | width4 = 250\n | caption4  = [[Jet Aviation]] 787-8 VIP\n | image3 = 777x model.png\n | width3 = 250\n | caption3 = A [[scale model]] of a member of the [[777X]] family\n}}\n\n* '''[[747-8]]''': with a range of {{cvt|8,875|nmi|km}} with 100 passengers, eleven were ordered through December 2018, all delivered, and six were in service.<ref name=BBJ/> The VIP 747 is delivered by BBJ in a \"green\" condition, meaning there are no interior furnishings so that the owner can design it to personal preference.\n* '''[[B777]]''': -200LR and -300ER with a range of {{cvt|10,030 and 9,300|nmi|km}} with 75 passengers, thirteen were ordered through December 2018, all delivered, and nine were in service. The BBJ 777X succeeded the BBJ 777 in December 2018.<ref name=BBJ/>\n* '''[[777X|B777X]]''': -8 and -9 with a range of {{cvt|11,654 and 11,000|nmi|km}} with 75 passengers. On December 10, 2018, Boeing launched BBJ variants of the [[777X]] at the [[Middle East Business Aviation Association]] Show. The BBJ 777-8 offers a 3,256 sq. ft. (302.5 sq m) cabin, while the BBJ 777-9 provides a 3,689 sq. ft. (342.7 sq m) variant.<ref>{{cite press release |url= https://boeing.mediaroom.com/2018-12-10-Boeing-Launches-Longest-Range-Business-Jet-Ever-with-BBJ-777X |title= Boeing Launches Longest-Range Business Jet Ever with BBJ 777X|date= Dec 10, 2018 |publisher= Boeing}}</ref><ref name=BBJ/>\n* '''[[B787]]''': the \u22128 and the \u22129 have a range of {{cvt|9,945 and 9,485|nmi|km}} with 25 passengers, fifteen were ordered through September 2018 with twelve delivered and four in service.<ref name=BBJ/> As with the 747, the VIP 787 is delivered by BBJ in a \"green\" condition.\n\n====Specifications====\n{| style=\"text-align: center\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Boeing Business Jets<ref name=BBJ/>\n|-\n! Variant !! BBJ 787-8 !! BBJ 787-9 !! BBJ 777-8 !! BBJ 777-9 !! BBJ 747-8\n|- \n! Cabin\n| 2,415 sq.ft / 224.4 m\u00b2 \n| 2,775 sq.ft / 257.8 m\u00b2\n| 3,256 sq.ft / 302.5 m\u00b2\n| 3,689 sq.ft / 342.7 m\u00b2  \n| {{cvt|4786\u20135179|sqft|m2|disp=br}}{{efn|without/with overhead}}\n|- \n! Cargo \n| 4,862 cu.ft / 138.2 m\u00b3\n| 6,162 cu.ft / 174.5 m\u00b3\n| 6,010 cu.ft / 170.2 m\u00b3\n| 7,705 cu.ft / 218.2 m\u00b3\n| {{cvt|6,940|cuft|m3|sigfig=4}}\n|- \n! Length\n| {{convert|186|ft|1|in|m|abbr=on|2}}\n| {{convert|206|ft|1|in|m|abbr=on|2}}\n| 229&nbsp;ft / 69.8 m\n| 251&nbsp;ft 9 in / 76.7 m\n| 250&nbsp;ft 2 in / 76.3 m\n|-\n! Span \n| colspan=2 | {{convert|197|ft|3|in|m|abbr=on|2}} \n| colspan=2 | 235&nbsp;ft 5 in / 71.80 m\n| 224&nbsp;ft 7 in / 68.4 m\n|-\n! Height\n| {{convert|55|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on|2}}\n| {{convert|55|ft|10|in|m|abbr=on}}\n| 64&nbsp;ft / 19.5 m\n| 64&nbsp;ft 7 in / 19.7 m\n| 63&nbsp;ft 6 in / 19.4 m\n|-  \n! [[Maximum takeoff weight|MTOW]]\n| 502,500&nbsp;lb / 227,930&nbsp;kg\n| 560,000&nbsp;lb / 254,011&nbsp;kg\n| colspan=2 | 775,000&nbsp;lb / 351,550&nbsp;kg\n| 987,000&nbsp;lb / 447,700&nbsp;kg\n|-  \n! max [[Payload]] <!-- = Maximum zero fuel weight - OEW-->\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:355000-277200}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:400000-295000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:527300-412300}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:538105-450000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:651000-536100}}|lb|kg|0}}\n|-  \n! [[Operating empty weight|OEW]]\n| {{cvt|277,200|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|295,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|412,300|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|450,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|536,100|lb|kg|0}}\n|-\n! Furnishings\n| {{cvt|40,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|45,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|55,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|65,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|100,000|lb|kg|0}}\n|-\n! [[Manufacturer's empty weight|MEW]] <!-- = OEW - interior allowance-->\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:277200-40000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:295000-45000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:412300-55000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:450000-65000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:536100-100000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n|-\n! Fuel capacity\n| {{cvt|33,340|USgal|l|0}}\n| {{cvt|33,380|USgal|l|0}}\n| colspan=2 | 52,300 US gal / 197,977 L \n| 63,034USgal / 238,610L\n|-\n! Engines\n| colspan=2 | [[General Electric GEnx|GEnx-1B]] or [[Rolls-Royce Trent 1000]]\n| colspan=2 | [[General Electric GE9X]]\n| [[General Electric GEnx|GEnx-2B67]]\n|-\n! Range\n| {{cvt|9,945|nmi|km|0}}{{efn|name=25pax|25 passengers}}\n| {{cvt|9,485|nmi|km|0}}{{efn|name=25pax}}\n| {{cvt|11,654|nmi|km|0}}{{efn|name=75pax|75 passengers}}\n| {{cvt|11,000|nmi|km|0}}{{efn|name=75pax}}\n| {{cvt|8,875|nmi|km|0}}{{efn|100 passengers}}\n|}\n\n==Operators==\n[[File:RAAF Boeing 737-7DT(BBJ) CBR Gilbert-2.jpg|thumb|[[Royal Australian Air Force|Royal Australian Air Force]] 737-700 BBJ]]\n[[File:P4-KAZ Boeing B737-7EJ W BBJ B737 (9784776696).jpg|thumb|right|[[Armed Forces of the Republic of Kazakhstan]] 737-700/BBJ]]\n[[File:State of Kuwait Boeing 737-9BQ(ER) (Boeing Business Jet 3) 9K-GCC.jpg|thumb|[[Kuwait|State of Kuwait]] 737-900/BBJ3 ]]\n[[File:Royal Jet Boeing 737-700 KvW.jpg|thumb|right|737-700/BBJ of the [[Abu Dhabi]] airline [[Royal Jet]]]]\n\n===Private===\nBBJs were initially operated by Fortune 100 companies like [[Aramco]] and [[Tracinda]]; [[NetJets]], casinos like the [[Las Vegas Sands]], but\nthe 2008 recession put ultra large jets under scrutiny and were divested by many companies including [[L Brands|The Limited]], [[General Electric]] and [[Occidental Petroleum]]; or Chinese companies to avoid wealth displays.<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nBBJ are now operated by private firms and individuals:  Fresno's Assemi Group, Miami's [[Crescent Heights (company)|Crescent Heights]], Wichita's [[Town & Country Food Market]], Funair Corp., toymaker [[Ty Inc.]], Fortress Transportation & Instructure, [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]], John Travolta, [[Steven Spielberg]], Washington Corp., [[Tutor Saliba]] or pachinko king [[Hideyuki Busujima]], with many registrations hiding their owners\u2019 identities.<ref name=BCA7jan2019/>\n\n===State VIP users===\nMost BBJs are operated by governments for [[very important person|VIP]] transport in U.S., Australia and Africa, plus Colombia, Turkey and India, [[United Arab Emirates|UAE]], Jordan, Malaysia, South Africa or Tunisia; or Middle East oil barons like Abu Dhabi, Dubai and Saudi Arabia royalty.<ref name=BCA7jan2019/>\n\n; {{flag|Australia}}: [[Royal Australian Air Force]] (2) leased BBJ737\n::* [[No. 34 Squadron RAAF]] for VIP transport\n; {{flag|Belarus}}: [[Belarus Air Force]] (1)\n::* Boeing 767-32K (EW-001PB) BBJ2 for Government VIP flight<ref>https://www.planespotters.net/airframe/boeing-767-300-ew-001pb-belarus-government/ep7n4e</ref>\n; {{flag|Colombia}}: [[Colombian Air Force]] (1)\n::* Grupo de Vuelos Especiales 82 Escuadr\u00f3n de Transporte Especial 821 for VIP transport\n; {{flag|India}}: [[Indian Air Force]] (3) \n::* Air HQ Communication Squadron for Government VIP use\n; {{flag|Indonesia}}: [[Indonesian Presidential Aircraft|Presidency]] (1)  BBJ2 for Government VVIP flight.<ref>{{cite news|title =RI \u2018Air Force One\u2019 will not be armed  | date = 14 April 2014 | author = tjs |newspaper = The Jakarta Post |url = http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2014/04/14/ri-air-force-one-will-not-be-armed.html | accessdate = 17 January 2015}}</ref>\n; {{flag|Kazakhstan}}: [[Government of Kazakhstan]] (1)\n; {{flag|Kuwait}}: [[Government of Kuwait]] (2)\n; {{flag|Madagascar}}: Presidency (1)\n; {{flag|Malaysia}}: [[Royal Malaysian Air Force]] (1) \n::* 1st Division 2 Squadron for VIP\n; {{flag|Mexico}}: [[Mexican Air Force]] (1)\n::* General Coordination of the Presidential Air Transport Unit - 787 for government VIP flight, currently stored.\n; {{flag|Morocco}}: [[Royal Moroccan Air Force]] (2)\n; {{flag|Netherlands}}: [[Politics of the Netherlands|Government of the Kingdom of the Netherlands]](1)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/dutch-to-replace-royal-transport-with-737-bbj-436119/|title=Dutch to replace Royal transport with 737 BBJ|author=|date=11 April 2017|website=flightglobal.com|accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n;{{flag|Niger}}: Government of Niger (1) \n::* 5U-BAG for government VIP flight stored since 2014.<ref>https://www.planespotters.net/airframe/boeing-737-200-5u-bag-niger-government/349nxr</ref>\n; {{flag|Nigeria}}: [[Nigerian Air Force]] (1)\n::* NAF Mobility Command\n; {{flag|Poland}}: [[Polish Air Force]] \n:: * 3rd Transport Aviation Wing Aviation Squadron for government VIP flight, beginning in 2020 (2 BBJ2)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ch-aviation.com/portal/news/54827-polish-govt-orders-three-vip-configured-b737nextgens|title=Polish gov't orders three VIP-configured B737NextGens|author=|date=|website=ch-aviation.com|accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n; {{flag|Qatar}}: [[Qatar Amiri Flight]] (1)\n::* sold to Moroccan Government in 2010\n; {{flag|South Africa}}: [[South African Air Force]] (1)\n::* 21 Squadron SAAF for VIP transport\n; {{flag|Tunisia}}: [[Tunisia|Republic of Tunisia Government]] (1)\n; {{flag|United Arab Emirates}}: [[Abu Dhabi Amiri Flight]] (9), [[Royal Jet]] (6) BBJ1 for Government VIP flight<ref name=\"aerospace-technology\">http://www.aerospace-technology.com/projects/bbj/{{Unreliable source?|reason=domain on WP:BLACKLIST|date=June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Orders and deliveries==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Through December 2018<ref name=BBJ/>\n! Aircraft        \n! 737 !! BBJ !! MAX !! 757 !! 767 !! 777 !! 787 !! 744 !! 748\n! Total\n|-\n! Orders\n|  16 || 169 ||  21 ||   5 ||   8 ||  13 ||  15 ||   3 ||  11\n! 261\n|-\n! Deliveries\n|  16 || 167 ||   2 ||   5 ||   8 ||  13 ||  12 ||   3 ||  11\n! 237\n|-\n! In service\n|  16 || 159 ||   0 ||   5 ||   8 ||   9 ||   4 ||   3 ||   6\n! 210\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Aircontent\n|related=\n* [[Boeing C-40 Clipper]]\n|similar aircraft=\n* [[Airbus Corporate Jets]]\n|lists=\n* [[Air transports of heads of state and government]]\n* [[List of active United States military aircraft]]\n* [[List of civil aircraft]]\n* [[List of military aircraft of the United States]]\n}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons and category|Boeing Business Jets}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.boeing.com/commercial/bbj}}\n\n{{Boeing airliners}}\n{{Boeing 737 family}}\n\n[[Category:Boeing aircraft|Business Jet]]\n[[Category:United States business aircraft]]\n[[Category:Boeing 737]]\n[[Category:Boeing 747]]\n[[Category:Boeing 777]]\n[[Category:Boeing 787 Dreamliner]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Executive transport variants of several Boeing airliners}}\n<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox aircraft begin\n| name = Boeing Business Jet\n| image = Boeing's commercial aircraft in BBJ livery.jpg\n| caption = Artist's impression of the entire BBJ family\n}}{{Infobox aircraft type\n| type = [[Business jet]]\n| manufacturer = [[Boeing Commercial Airplanes]]\n| designer = \n| first flight = September 4, 1998\n| introduced = 1999\n| retired = \n| status = \n| primary user = \n| more users = \n| produced = 1998\u2013present\n| number built = 237 (as of December 31, 2018) (including BBJ1, BBJ2, BBJ3, 747BBJ, 757BBJ, 767BBJ, 777BBJ & 787BBJ)<ref name=\"boeing.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boeing.com/commercial/bbj/#/orders-and-deliveries|title=Boeing: Boeing Business Jets|author=|date=|website=boeing.com|accessdate=23 February 2019}}</ref>\n| unit cost = MAX7: [[United States dollar|US$]]91.2M, MAX8: $99M, MAX9: $107.9M (2019)<ref name=BCA-2019>{{cite magazine |url= https://aviationweek.com/site-files/aviationweek.com/files/datasheets/gated/BCA_201906.pdf |title= Purchase Planning Handbook |magazine= Business & Commercial Aviation |date= June 2019 |publisher= Aviation Week Network |url-access= subscription}}</ref>\n| developed from = \n| variants with their own articles = \n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Boeing Business Jet''' series are variants of [[Boeing Commercial Airplanes|Boeing]] [[jet airliner]]s for the [[corporate jet]] market.\n\nThe '''BBJ''' designation denotes the business jets based upon the [[Boeing 737|737]] series airliners. These aircraft usually seat between 25 and 50 passengers within a luxurious configuration. This may include a master bedroom, a washroom with showers, a conference/dining area, and a living area. Boeing Business Jets also has corporate jet configurations based on the [[Boeing 737 MAX|737 MAX]], [[Boeing 777x|777X]], [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner|787 Dreamliner]] and [[Boeing 747-8|747-8 Intercontinental]], which are known as '''737 MAX VIP''', '''777X VIP''', '''787 VIP''', and '''747-8 VIP''', respectively.\n\nThe BBJ division offers 11 products derived from Boeing's airliners.<ref name=ain2015-05-16>{{cite news |first=Kerry |last=Lynch |url=http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/business-aviation/2015-05-16/boeing-business-jets-confident-it-studies-combi |title=Boeing Business Jets confident as it studies Combi |work=Aviation International News |date= 16 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Models==\n\n===Narrow-body models===\n[[File:Boeing 737-75V BBJ AN1425895.jpg|thumb|BBJ cabin]]\n\n<!--design-->\nThe first BBJ is based on the [[737-700]] with a stronger wing and landing gear from the [[737-800]].<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nAuxiliary belly fuel tanks extend range, over {{cvt|6,000|nmi|km}} with nine tanks ({{cvt|500|lb|kg}} empty each), but most operators install five auxiliary fuel tanks to fly up to {{cvt|5,400|nmi|km}}.<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nIn 2002, the -800-based BBJ2 offered a 25% larger cabin with a similar range with five tanks, with the 2009 BBJ3 based on the [[737-900]].<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\n[[Aviation Partners]] winglets gave the BBJ 5% more range.<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nA standard, retractable forward [[airstair]] allows for autonomous operations at remote airports.<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nEarly interiors were way over the {{cvt|13,000|lb|t}} allowance and the [[basic operating weight|BOW]]s reached {{cvt|104,000\u20138,000|lb}} over spec, but newer interiors can be 25% lighter for {{cvt|99,000\u2013100,000|lb|t}} empty weights.<ref name=BCA7jan2019/>\n\n<!--performance-->\nFuel burn is {{cvt|4,830|lb|t}} per hour at Mach 0.785, rising to over {{cvt|5,700|lb|t}} at Mach 0.82, twice as much as a faster [[Global 6000]].<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\n<!--maintenance-->\nDirect operating costs are $14,000 per hour, minor inspections come every 36 months and major inspections at 12-year for a 4\u20138 weeks down time.<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nAt 41,000 ft, cabin altitude can be lowered from 8,000&nbsp;ft to 6,500&nbsp;ft, but it reduces airframe life to 26,000 down from 50,000 cycles, much higher than purpose-built business jets.<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nMost operators fly their aircraft 200\u2013250 h per year with 6\u20138 passengers, 500\u2013800 h for corporations to less than 150\u2013200 h for individuals.<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nThe CFM56 service program costs $240\u2013260 per engine per hour, less than the [[Rolls-Royce BR700]], with the engines staying on wing for at least 12,000\u201313,000 h for most, and up to 25,000\u201330,000 h.<ref name=BCA7jan2019/>\n[[Fokker Technologies#Business units|Fokker Services]] were developing {{cvt|1.5|meter}} wide windows for the BBJ in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/business-aviation/2015-05-20/first-skyview-bbj|title=First SkyView for BBJ|author= David Donald |date= May 20, 2015 |work=AIN online}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/ebace-fokker-proposes-giant-window-to-boeing-business-399588/ |title= Fokker proposes giant window to Boeing Business Jets |date= 13 Apr 2015 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n<!-- operators-->\nTwenty years after the 1999 introduction, 150 BBJs had entered service, triple the initial forecast of 50. The 2008 recession put ultra large jets under scrutiny and were divested by some companies. Some BBJs are operated by governments for [[VIP transport]].<ref name=BCA7jan2019>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/business-aviation/boeing-business-jet-why-go-big-because-you-can |title= Boeing Business Jet: Why Go Big? Because You Can |date= Jan 7, 2019 |author= Fred George |work= Business & Commercial Aviation}}</ref>\n\n<!--competition-->\nAfter the launch of the BBJ, [[Airbus]] followed suit with the launch of the [[Airbus Corporate Jets|Airbus ACJ]] derived from its [[Airbus A319|A319]] airliner, then the larger A320 and the smaller [[Airbus A318|A318]] Elite. Other smaller competitors include the [[Embraer Lineage]], the [[Bombardier Global Express]], the [[Gulfstream G550]] and the [[Gulfstream G650]]. A BBJ costs {{usd|9.57\u201310.13}} per nautical mile to operate, whereas the faster G650ER costs $5.87 to 6.33.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviationweek.com/site-files/aviationweek.com/files/gallery_images/BCA_2015_Operations_Planning_Guide_6b.jpg?1440787936|title= Mission Costs for Ultra-Long-Range Jets Table|work= Aviation Week |date= May 2015}}</ref>\n\n* '''BBJ''', or less frequently '''BBJ1''', is based on the 737-700, and formed the basis for the 737-700ER. This was the initial variant. In [[United States Navy]] service, this is known as the [[Boeing C-40 Clipper|C-40B Clipper]].\n* '''BBJ2''' is based on the 737-800.\n* '''BBJ3''' is based on the 737-900ER.\n* '''BBJ C''' is a variant of the BBJ featuring the \"quick change\" capabilities of the 737-700C. This allows the aircraft to be used for executive duty during one flight, and to be quickly reconfigured for cargo duty for the next flight.\n* '''BBJ MAX 8''' and '''BBJ MAX 9''' are variants of the [[Boeing 737 MAX]] 8 and 9 with new [[CFM LEAP]]-1B engines and advanced winglets providing 13% better fuel burn; the BBJ MAX 8 will have a {{cvt|6,325|nmi|km|-1}} range and the BBJ MAX 9 a {{cvt|6,255|nmi|km|-1}} range.<ref>{{cite press release |url= http://boeing.mediaroom.com/2012-10-29-Boeing-Business-Jets-to-Offer-the-BBJ-MAX |title= Boeing Business Jets to Offer the BBJ MAX |publisher= Boeing |date= October 29, 2012 |access-date=October 30, 2012}}</ref> The '''BBJ MAX 7''' was unveiled in October 2016 and will have a {{cvt|7,000|nmi|km|-1}} range, with 10% lower operating costs than the original BBJ while having a longer cabin and more under-floor baggage space.<ref>{{cite press release |url= http://boeing.mediaroom.com/news-releases-statements?item=129797 |title= Boeing Business Jets Unveils BBJ MAX 7 |date= October 31, 2016 |publisher= Boeing |access-date=November 1, 2016}}</ref> The MAX BBJ 8 first flew on April 16, 2018, and will reach {{cvt|6,640|nmi|km|-1}} with an auxiliary fuel tank.<ref>{{cite press release |url= http://boeing.mediaroom.com/2018-04-16-Boeing-Business-Jets-Celebrates-Flyaway-of-First-BBJ-MAX-Airplane |title= Milestone paves the way for delivery of the newest version of the best-selling business jetliner |date= April 16, 2018 |publisher= Boeing}}</ref> It was first delivered by mid-October.<ref>{{cite press release |url= https://boeing.mediaroom.com/2018-10-15-Boeing-Business-Jets-Delivers-First-BBJ-MAX-Airplane |title= Boeing Business Jets Delivers First BBJ MAX Airplane |date= Oct 15, 2018 |publisher= Boeing}}</ref>\n\n{{seealso|Boeing 737 MAX groundings}}\n\n====Specifications====\n{| style=\"text-align: center\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Boeing Business Jets<ref name=BBJ>{{cite web |url= https://www.boeing.com/commercial/bbj |title= Boeing Business Jets |date= December 2018 |publisher= Boeing}}</ref>\n|-\n! Variant !! BBJ MAX 7 !! BBJ MAX 8 !! BBJ MAX 9 \n|- \n! Cabin\n| 884 sq ft / 82.1 m\u00b2\n| 1,025 sq ft / 95.2 m\u00b2\n| 1,120 sq ft / 104.1 m\u00b2 \n|- \n! Cargo \n| 274 cu.ft / 7.8 m\u00b3\n| 654 cu.ft / 18.5 m\u00b3\n| 821 cu.ft /23.2 m\u00b3\n|- \n! Length\n| 116&nbsp;ft 8 in / 35.56 m\n| 129&nbsp;ft 8 in / 39.52 m\n| 138&nbsp;ft 4 in / 42.16 m\n|- \n! Span \u00d7 Height\n| colspan=3 | 117&nbsp;ft 10 in / 35.92 m \u00d7 40&nbsp;ft 4 in / 12.3 m\n|-  \n! [[Maximum takeoff weight|MTOW]]\n| 177,000&nbsp;lb / 80,286&nbsp;kg\n| 181,200&nbsp;lb / 82,191&nbsp;kg\n| 194,700&nbsp;lb / 88,314&nbsp;kg\n|-  \n! max [[Payload]] <!-- = Maximum zero fuel weight - OEW-->\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:138700-106330}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:145400-109890}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:156500-117900}}|lb|kg|0}}\n|-  \n! [[Operating empty weight|OEW]]\n| {{cvt|106,330|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|109,890|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|117,900|lb|kg|0}}\n|-\n! Furnishings\n| {{cvt|16,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|18,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|21,000|lb|kg|0}}\n|-\n! [[Manufacturer's empty weight|MEW]] <!-- = OEW - interior allowance-->\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:106330-16000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:109890-18000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:117900-21000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n|-\n! Fuel capacity{{efn|auxiliary tanks: 7 for MAX 7/8, 8 for MAX 9}}\n| {{cvt|10,464|USgal|l|0}}\n| {{cvt|10,470|USgal|l|0}}\n| {{cvt|11,005|USgal|l|0}}\n|-\n! Engines (2\u00d7)\n| colspan=3 | [[CFM International LEAP]]\n|-\n! Range (8 pax)\n| {{cvt|7,000|nmi|km|0}}\n| {{cvt|6,640|nmi|km|0}}\n| {{cvt|6,515|nmi|km|0}}\n|}\n\n===Wide-body models===\n\n{{multiple image\n | direction = vertical\n | image1 = A7-HBJ 03122015LHR (23226682739) (cropped).jpg\n | width1 = 250\n | caption1 = [[Qatar Amiri Flight]] 747-8 VIP\n | image2 = Boeing 777-24Q-ER AN0433002 (cropped).jpg\n | width2 = 250\n | caption2  = [[Mid East Jet]] 777-200 VIP\n | image4 = Jet Aviation Flight Services, Boeing 787-8 Dreamliner, N28MS (cropped).jpg\n | width4 = 250\n | caption4  = [[Jet Aviation]] 787-8 VIP\n | image3 = 777x model.png\n | width3 = 250\n | caption3 = A [[scale model]] of a member of the [[777X]] family\n}}\n\n* '''[[747-8]]''': with a range of {{cvt|8,875|nmi|km}} with 100 passengers, eleven were ordered through December 2018, all delivered, and six were in service.<ref name=BBJ/> The VIP 747 is delivered by BBJ in a \"green\" condition, meaning there are no interior furnishings so that the owner can design it to personal preference.\n* '''[[B777]]''': -200LR and -300ER with a range of {{cvt|10,030 and 9,300|nmi|km}} with 75 passengers, thirteen were ordered through December 2018, all delivered, and nine were in service. The BBJ 777X succeeded the BBJ 777 in December 2018.<ref name=BBJ/>\n* '''[[777X|B777X]]''': -8 and -9 with a range of {{cvt|11,654 and 11,000|nmi|km}} with 75 passengers. On December 10, 2018, Boeing launched BBJ variants of the [[777X]] at the [[Middle East Business Aviation Association]] Show. The BBJ 777-8 offers a 3,256 sq. ft. (302.5 sq m) cabin, while the BBJ 777-9 provides a 3,689 sq. ft. (342.7 sq m) variant.<ref>{{cite press release |url= https://boeing.mediaroom.com/2018-12-10-Boeing-Launches-Longest-Range-Business-Jet-Ever-with-BBJ-777X |title= Boeing Launches Longest-Range Business Jet Ever with BBJ 777X|date= Dec 10, 2018 |publisher= Boeing}}</ref><ref name=BBJ/>\n* '''[[B787]]''': the \u22128 and the \u22129 have a range of {{cvt|9,945 and 9,485|nmi|km}} with 25 passengers, fifteen were ordered through September 2018 with twelve delivered and four in service.<ref name=BBJ/> As with the 747, the VIP 787 is delivered by BBJ in a \"green\" condition.\n\n====Specifications====\n{| style=\"text-align: center\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Boeing Business Jets<ref name=BBJ/>\n|-\n! Variant !! BBJ 787-8 !! BBJ 787-9 !! BBJ 777-8 !! BBJ 777-9 !! BBJ 747-8\n|- \n! Cabin\n| 2,415 sq.ft / 224.4 m\u00b2 \n| 2,775 sq.ft / 257.8 m\u00b2\n| 3,256 sq.ft / 302.5 m\u00b2\n| 3,689 sq.ft / 342.7 m\u00b2  \n| {{cvt|4786\u20135179|sqft|m2|disp=br}}{{efn|without/with overhead}}\n|- \n! Cargo \n| 4,862 cu.ft / 138.2 m\u00b3\n| 6,162 cu.ft / 174.5 m\u00b3\n| 6,010 cu.ft / 170.2 m\u00b3\n| 7,705 cu.ft / 218.2 m\u00b3\n| {{cvt|6,940|cuft|m3|sigfig=4}}\n|- \n! Length\n| {{convert|186|ft|1|in|m|abbr=on|2}}\n| {{convert|206|ft|1|in|m|abbr=on|2}}\n| 229&nbsp;ft / 69.8 m\n| 251&nbsp;ft 9 in / 76.7 m\n| 250&nbsp;ft 2 in / 76.3 m\n|-\n! Span \n| colspan=2 | {{convert|197|ft|3|in|m|abbr=on|2}} \n| colspan=2 | 235&nbsp;ft 5 in / 71.80 m\n| 224&nbsp;ft 7 in / 68.4 m\n|-\n! Height\n| {{convert|55|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on|2}}\n| {{convert|55|ft|10|in|m|abbr=on}}\n| 64&nbsp;ft / 19.5 m\n| 64&nbsp;ft 7 in / 19.7 m\n| 63&nbsp;ft 6 in / 19.4 m\n|-  \n! [[Maximum takeoff weight|MTOW]]\n| 502,500&nbsp;lb / 227,930&nbsp;kg\n| 560,000&nbsp;lb / 254,011&nbsp;kg\n| colspan=2 | 775,000&nbsp;lb / 351,550&nbsp;kg\n| 987,000&nbsp;lb / 447,700&nbsp;kg\n|-  \n! max [[Payload]] <!-- = Maximum zero fuel weight - OEW-->\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:355000-277200}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:400000-295000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:527300-412300}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:538105-450000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:651000-536100}}|lb|kg|0}}\n|-  \n! [[Operating empty weight|OEW]]\n| {{cvt|277,200|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|295,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|412,300|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|450,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|536,100|lb|kg|0}}\n|-\n! Furnishings\n| {{cvt|40,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|45,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|55,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|65,000|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|100,000|lb|kg|0}}\n|-\n! [[Manufacturer's empty weight|MEW]] <!-- = OEW - interior allowance-->\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:277200-40000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:295000-45000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:412300-55000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:450000-65000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n| {{cvt|{{#expr:536100-100000}}|lb|kg|0}}\n|-\n! Fuel capacity\n| {{cvt|33,340|USgal|l|0}}\n| {{cvt|33,380|USgal|l|0}}\n| colspan=2 | 52,300 US gal / 197,977 L \n| 63,034USgal / 238,610L\n|-\n! Engines\n| colspan=2 | [[General Electric GEnx|GEnx-1B]] or [[Rolls-Royce Trent 1000]]\n| colspan=2 | [[General Electric GE9X]]\n| [[General Electric GEnx|GEnx-2B67]]\n|-\n! Range\n| {{cvt|9,945|nmi|km|0}}{{efn|name=25pax|25 passengers}}\n| {{cvt|9,485|nmi|km|0}}{{efn|name=25pax}}\n| {{cvt|11,654|nmi|km|0}}{{efn|name=75pax|75 passengers}}\n| {{cvt|11,000|nmi|km|0}}{{efn|name=75pax}}\n| {{cvt|8,875|nmi|km|0}}{{efn|100 passengers}}\n|}\n\n==Operators==\n[[File:RAAF Boeing 737-7DT(BBJ) CBR Gilbert-2.jpg|thumb|[[Royal Australian Air Force|Royal Australian Air Force]] 737-700 BBJ]]\n[[File:P4-KAZ Boeing B737-7EJ W BBJ B737 (9784776696).jpg|thumb|right|[[Armed Forces of the Republic of Kazakhstan]] 737-700/BBJ]]\n[[File:State of Kuwait Boeing 737-9BQ(ER) (Boeing Business Jet 3) 9K-GCC.jpg|thumb|[[Kuwait|State of Kuwait]] 737-900/BBJ3 ]]\n[[File:Royal Jet Boeing 737-700 KvW.jpg|thumb|right|737-700/BBJ of the [[Abu Dhabi]] airline [[Royal Jet]]]]\n\n===Private===\nBBJs were initially operated by Fortune 100 companies like [[Aramco]] and [[Tracinda]]; [[NetJets]], casinos like the [[Las Vegas Sands]], but\nthe 2008 recession put ultra large jets under scrutiny and were divested by many companies including [[L Brands|The Limited]], [[General Electric]] and [[Occidental Petroleum]]; or Chinese companies to avoid wealth displays.<!--<ref name=BCA7jan2019>-->\nBBJ are now operated by private firms and individuals:  Fresno's [[Assemi Group]], Miami's [[Crescent Heights (company)|Crescent Heights]], Wichita's [[Town & Country Food Market]], [[Funair Corp.]], toymaker [[Ty Inc.]], [[Fortress Transportation & Instructure]], [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]], John Travolta, [[Steven Spielberg]], [[Washington Corp.]], [[Tutor Saliba]] or pachinko king [[Hideyuki Busujima]], with many registrations hiding their owners\u2019 identities.<ref name=BCA7jan2019/>\n\n===State VIP users===\nMost BBJs are operated by governments for [[very important person|VIP]] transport in U.S., Australia and Africa, plus Colombia, Turkey and India, [[United Arab Emirates|UAE]], Jordan, Malaysia, South Africa or Tunisia; or [[Middle East oil]] barons like Abu Dhabi, Dubai and Saudi Arabia royalty.<ref name=BCA7jan2019/>\n\n; {{flag|Australia}}: [[Royal Australian Air Force]] (2) leased BBJ737\n::* [[No. 34 Squadron RAAF]] for VIP transport\n; {{flag|Belarus}}: [[Belarus Air Force]] (1)\n::* Boeing 767-32K (EW-001PB) BBJ2 for Government VIP flight<ref>https://www.planespotters.net/airframe/boeing-767-300-ew-001pb-belarus-government/ep7n4e</ref>\n; {{flag|Colombia}}: [[Colombian Air Force]] (1)\n::* Grupo de Vuelos Especiales 82 Escuadr\u00f3n de Transporte Especial 821 for VIP transport\n; {{flag|India}}: [[Indian Air Force]] (3) \n::* Air HQ Communication Squadron for Government VIP use\n; {{flag|Indonesia}}: [[Indonesian Presidential Aircraft|Presidency]] (1)  BBJ2 for Government VVIP flight.<ref>{{cite news|title =RI \u2018Air Force One\u2019 will not be armed  | date = 14 April 2014 | author = tjs |newspaper = The Jakarta Post |url = http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2014/04/14/ri-air-force-one-will-not-be-armed.html | accessdate = 17 January 2015}}</ref>\n; {{flag|Kazakhstan}}: [[Government of Kazakhstan]] (1)\n; {{flag|Kuwait}}: [[Government of Kuwait]] (2)\n; {{flag|Madagascar}}: Presidency (1)\n; {{flag|Malaysia}}: [[Royal Malaysian Air Force]] (1) \n::* 1st Division 2 Squadron for VIP\n; {{flag|Mexico}}: [[Mexican Air Force]] (1)\n::* General Coordination of the Presidential Air Transport Unit - 787 for government VIP flight, currently stored.\n; {{flag|Morocco}}: [[Royal Moroccan Air Force]] (2)\n; {{flag|Netherlands}}: [[Politics of the Netherlands|Government of the Kingdom of the Netherlands]](1)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/dutch-to-replace-royal-transport-with-737-bbj-436119/|title=Dutch to replace Royal transport with 737 BBJ|author=|date=11 April 2017|website=flightglobal.com|accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n;{{flag|Niger}}: Government of Niger (1) \n::* 5U-BAG for government VIP flight stored since 2014.<ref>https://www.planespotters.net/airframe/boeing-737-200-5u-bag-niger-government/349nxr</ref>\n; {{flag|Nigeria}}: [[Nigerian Air Force]] (1)\n::* NAF Mobility Command\n; {{flag|Poland}}: [[Polish Air Force]] \n:: * 3rd Transport Aviation Wing Aviation Squadron for government VIP flight, beginning in 2020 (2 BBJ2)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ch-aviation.com/portal/news/54827-polish-govt-orders-three-vip-configured-b737nextgens|title=Polish gov't orders three VIP-configured B737NextGens|author=|date=|website=ch-aviation.com|accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n; {{flag|Qatar}}: [[Qatar Amiri Flight]] (1)\n::* sold to Moroccan Government in 2010\n; {{flag|South Africa}}: [[South African Air Force]] (1)\n::* 21 Squadron SAAF for VIP transport\n; {{flag|Tunisia}}: [[Tunisia|Republic of Tunisia Government]] (1)\n; {{flag|United Arab Emirates}}: [[Abu Dhabi Amiri Flight]] (9), [[Royal Jet]] (6) BBJ1 for Government VIP flight<ref name=\"aerospace-technology\">http://www.aerospace-technology.com/projects/bbj/{{Unreliable source?|reason=domain on WP:BLACKLIST|date=June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Orders and deliveries==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Through December 2018<ref name=BBJ/>\n! Aircraft        \n! 737 !! BBJ !! MAX !! 757 !! 767 !! 777 !! 787 !! 744 !! 748\n! Total\n|-\n! Orders\n|  16 || 169 ||  21 ||   5 ||   8 ||  13 ||  15 ||   3 ||  11\n! 261\n